    "summary": "Sparta (founded traditionally c. 900 BC from the synoikism of villages in the Eurotas valley of Laconia) was ancient Greece's most distinctive city-state — a militarized society organized entirely around the production of warriors, which dominated the Greek mainland through military supremacy for over three centuries. Unlike Athens, Sparta produced little art or literature but created a social system so extreme and so effective at its own goals that it fascinated ancient and modern observers alike.\n\nSparta's society was built on the exploitation of the Helots — a conquered enslaved population that farmed Spartan land, outnumbering Spartan citizens perhaps 7:1. The constant threat of Helot revolt (suppressed periodically with great violence in the krypteia, a ritualized terror program) drove Spartans to maintain constant military readiness. The Spartan education system (agoge) took boys from their families at age 7 for collective military training until age 30, producing soldiers of legendary quality but citizens who had sacrificed most aspects of individual life. The [[event:1930|Lycurgan Reforms Sparta]] attributed to the lawgiver Lycurgus codified this system. Sparta's military reputation was sealed at Thermopylae (480 BC) and the final defeat of Athens in the [[event:1010|Peloponnesian War]].",
